<dl id="un2024d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="un2" href="#un2024">UN2: </a>  <a href="../../ff/unbs/un2all.htm#un2024d"> (VI.D.7) 24(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Belcher (handkerchief) <small>color t.b.a.</small> </blockquote> <dd class="well"><mm class="note">Note: Copied to <a name="s16026d" href="s16all.htm#s16026d">Sheet 16.026(d)</a>. </mm> <blockquote class="sources"><mark>Belcher</mark> (<i>Sporting</i>, 19 cent.). A <mark>handkerchief pattern</mark>, round spots, light or dark upon a dark or light ground. From a prize-fighter, Jim Belcher, who always carried into the ring a wiping handkerchief of this kind. After Belcher&apos;s time, the &lsquo;belcher&rsquo; split up into colours, every prize-fighter having his own tints. Belcher&apos;s original was white spots on dark blue ground. Until quite recent years, a spotted neck-tie was called a Belcher: now called a &lsquo;moon-tie&rsquo;. <small> J. Reading Ware, <a name="JRWP" href="/udra/udex.htm#jrwp"><cite title="source">Passing English of the Victorian Era</cite></a> (1909), 25</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
